</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> &quot;Ray Blockley&quot; &lt;rayblock...@ntlworld.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-09-30T06:47:00 </POSTDATE>
Hi folks,

Was racking off my first pressing yesterday and in two of the containers (which were slow to start) there was a distinct layer forming on top of the must, about 50mm thick, brown, jelly-like consistency. I was worried it was something like Mother of Vinegar, but the juice underneath was clear, slightly sparkling and sweet.

Have I obtained an accidental partial keeve?

I racked off the clear juice until the brown jelly started to appear in the pipe, leaving behind around half a gallon (out of 6) of what looked like wobbly coffee custard. The now blended and under air-lock cider is going great guns.

Any thoughts?

Cheers,

Ray.
