On the subject of chapeau brun:

I have recently started brewing my first batch of cider (only two
gallons, a veritable guppy in the ukcider pond). Following juicing, I
threw in some pectolase and Campden tablets and left for 24 hours.
During this settling period, a brown head developed; I subsequently
pitched some yeast in and left to ferment.

There is not a huge volume of detailed information about keeving out
there: my question is, should I have racked off the juice prior to
starting fermentation, and have I spoiled my first batch by not doing
so?

I should point out at this point that my purpose to adding the enzyme
was purely to eliminate the pectin haze and increase the amount of
sugar available for fermentation, not to limit the nutrients available
to allow a sweet cider to be brewed. Over the past week of brewing I
have observed the sediment in the bottom of the demijohns slowly
disappearing, and the brown head slowly being replaced by a healthy
yeasty one. Once fermentation started, it has progressed at a steady
rate and shows no sign of slowing down (our house is quite cold at the
moment, so this may just be down to the lower temperature). I am keen
to known whether the taste will be anything like the smell coming out
the fermentation lock though!
