<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
Jon Noble wrote:

&gt; There is not a huge volume of detailed information about keeving out
&gt; there:
">

If you go to my website and type 'keeving' into the search box you get
15 hits. Not a huge amount, but a start.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;my question is, should I have racked off the juice prior to
&gt; starting fermentation, and have I spoiled my first batch by not doing
&gt; so?
">

You will not achieve a proper keeve if you use Pectolase, because it is
a broad spectrum pectolytic enzyme with depolymerisisng activity which
will destroy the required gel. You need a special enzyme which contains
just pectin methyl esterase and not the depolymerising enzymes. (What
happened to Ray is that he had enough of this enzyme present naturally
in his fruit, hence his natural chapeau brun)

You have not done any harm by not racking, but you're not going to get a
naturally sweet cider this way even if you had racked (unless your
juice was stonkingly low in nutrients - and by adding a cultured yeast
you have rather offset that possibility anyway. The point of keeving is
to stress and starve the yeast so that it gives up before all the sugar
is consumed).

Andrew Lea

